    <%- include('partials/header') %>

        <main>
            <h1>Major Findings</h1>
            <p>During the exploratory data analysis (EDA) phase, we observed that no single economic indicator
                follows a consistent pattern before every recession. Each historical U.S. recession was triggered by
                different factors — from oil shocks and aggressive Fed tightening to housing bubbles and a global
                pandemic. Because of this, rather than looking for one universal warning sign, we compared the current
                data (April 2024 – March 2026) for each of the six indicators against every pre-recession period across
                six time windows to determine which past recession today's economy most closely resembles.</p>
            <p>
                In comparison to the current economic conditions (2024-2026), we have excluded the inflation data. This
                is because the inflation data is only updated yearly and not available for 2025 onwards.
            </p>
            <section>
                <h2>1. Analysis Findings</h2>
                <h3 id="overall-ranking">1.1 Overall Recession Similarity Ranking</h3>
                <p>The two bar graphs below rank all eight recessions by their average similarity score across all
                    <strong>six indicators</strong> and all <strong>six time windows</strong>.
                </p>

                <figure>
                    <img src="/images/Major%20findings/Overall-Recession-similarity.png"
                        alt="Overall Recession Similarity Ranking">
                </figure>

                <p>Two recessions stand out as statistically notable matches to the current economic environment:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>2008</strong> is the clearest match to today, with the highest similarity in both
                        measures, followed by <strong>2020</strong> as the second closest.</li>
                    <li>Most other recessions show only moderate similarity (scores mostly between 40–59), meaning
                        today’s conditions are not strongly aligned with them.</li>
                    <li>DTW scores are consistently higher than Spearman, suggesting the overall patterns/trends look
                        similar, even if the exact relationships between indicators are weaker.</li>
                </ul>

                <br>
                <p>
                    Now, let's compare each ecnonomic indicators separately to see how the current trend (2024-2026)
                    compares to past pre-recession periods.
                </p>
                <h3>1.2 1-Year Trend Comparison (current vs top 2 matching periods per indicator)</h3>
                <p>Across all six indicators, the current 2024–2026 trend traces patterns that closely mirror
                    pre-recession trajectories from past downturns:</p>

                <table class="table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>What to look for in the graphs</th>
                            <th>Spearman (Trend Match)</th>
                            <th>DTW (Pattern Match)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Overall direction (up/down)</td>
                            <td>Do the lines rise and fall together at the same time?</td>
                            <td>Less important</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Timing of changes</td>
                            <td>Must match closely (peaks &amp; drops aligned)</td>
                            <td>Can differ (DTW adjusts timing)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Shape of the curve</td>
                            <td>Somewhat important</td>
                            <td>Most important — overall shape similarity</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Lag between lines</td>
                            <td>❌ Penalized</td>
                            <td>✅ Allowed (handles delays)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>When score is high</td>
                            <td>Lines move together at the same time</td>
                            <td>Lines look similar, even if shifted</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>What it tells you</td>
                            <td>"Is this behaving like past trends right now?"</td>
                            <td>"Does this pattern resemble past cycles?"</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

