                <br>
                <h3>1.4. Conclusion</h3>
                <p>Across all indicators and time windows analyzed, the <strong>current economic environment
                        (2024–2026)</strong> most
                    consistently resembles the period leading up to the <strong>2008 Great Recession</strong>, with the
                    <strong>2020 COVID
                        Pandemic</strong>
                    emerging as a secondary analogue. This alignment is not driven by any single metric but is
                    reinforced
                    across multiple indicators, notably in gold, interest rates, and equity markets.
                    While unemployment remains moderate and oil prices subdued, the convergence of signals across the
                    remaining indicators warrants serious attention. History does not repeat perfectly, but the patterns
                    observed here is difficult to dismiss. <strong>The data does not predict a recession with
                        certainty, but the signals are strong enough that they should not be ignored.</strong>
                </p>

